{{One source|date=June 2009}} {{Infobox writer | name= Francis Vielé-Griffin | image= Francis Vielé-Griffin, portrait.jpg | caption= | birth_date= {{birth date|df=yes|1864|5|26}} | birth_place= [[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk]], [[Virginia]], US | death_date= {{death date and age|df=yes|1937|11|12|1864|5|26}} | death_place= | occupation= Poet | influences= | influenced= | genre= [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolist]] | signature= }} {{French literature sidebar}} '''Francis Vielé-Griffin''' (May 26, 1864{{snd}}November 12, 1937), was a French [[Symbolism (arts)|symbolist]] poet. He was born at [[Norfolk, Virginia]], USA and was the son of [[Egbert Ludovicus Viele]].
Vielé-Griffin was educated in France and divided his time between Paris and [[Touraine]]. He was a writer of ''[[vers libre]]'' and founded the highly influential journal ''[[Entretiens politiques et littéraires]]'' (1890–92).{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=50}}
==Works== His volumes include:{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=50}} *''Cueille d'avril'' (1885) *''Les Cygnes'' (1887; new series, 1892) *''La Chevauchée d'Yeldis'' (1893) *''Swanhilde'', a dramatic poem (1894) *''Laus Veneris'' (1895), a volume of translations from [[Algernon Charles Swinburne|Swinburne]] *''Poèmes et Poésies'' (1895), a collection containing much of his earlier work *''Phocas le jardinier'' (1898) *''La Légende ailee de Wieland le Forgeron'' (1899), a dramatic poem. *''L'Amour sacré'' (1903), poems
