{{Other people|2=Meir HaKohen Shiff}} '''Meir HaKohen'''<ref name=book>{{Cite book|last=Trachtenberg|first=Joshua|title=Jewish Magic and Superstition|location=Philadelphia|publisher=[[University of Pennsylvania Press]]|year=2004|origyear=Originally published 1939|isbn=9780812218626|page=320}}</ref> was a [[German Jews|German]] [[Rabbi]]nical scholar of the end of the thirteenth century.<ref name=je>{{Jewish Encyclopedia|inline=1|title=MEÏR HA-KOHEN|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/10578-meir-ha-kohen|first1=Richard|last1=Gottheil|author-link1=|first2=M. |last2=Seligsohn|author-link2=|access-date=}}</ref> He authored ''Hagahot Maimuniot''<ref name=book/> (or ''Haggahot Maimuniyyot''<ref name=je/>) on [[Maimonides]]' ''[[Mishneh Torah]]''. [[Bartolocci]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Bartolocci|title=Bibliothecae Magnae Rabbinicae|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZNU_AAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=snippet&q=Vrbe%20Legem%20docuit&f=false|volume=iv|page=20|access-date=}}</ref> mistakenly identifies him with Meïr Ha-Kohen, a French scholar of the same century.<ref name=je/> He was a student of [[Meir of Rothenburg]].<ref name=jvl>[http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/haggahot-maimuniyyot Haggahot Maimuniyyot]</ref>
==Works== ''Hagahot Maimuniot'', authored by Meir HaCohen, is one of the most important sources for the halachic rulings of medieval Ashkenazi rabbis. It takes the form of a running commentary on the [[Mishneh Torah]] by [[Maimonides]], and nowadays commonly appears at the bottom of the page in many printed editions of Mishneh Torah. There is also a section entitled ''Teshuvot Maimuniot'' which appears at the end of each book of Mishneh Torah.<ref name=jvl/>
